{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656407"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:13:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:13:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18738"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18738"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.25,0.04,0.39,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79550"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11470"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64854"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9913"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27197"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79550"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOxygen exists in blood in two forms: bound to haemoglobin and dissolved in plasma. Understanding the relative contributions of each form is crucial for respiratory physiology.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the amount of oxygen dissolved in 100 ml blood at normal atmospheric pressure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0.3 mL","3 mL","10 mL","20 mL","30 mL"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct amount of \u003Cstrong\u003E0.3 mL \u003C/strong\u003Eper 100 mL blood represents the dissolved oxygen content in blood at normal atmospheric pressure (1 atm). This small amount accounts for only about 3% of the total oxygen content, with the majority being carried bound to haemoglobin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E3 mL per 100 mL blood\u003C/strong\u003E - This is 10 times higher than the actual dissolved oxygen content\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E10 mL per 100 mL blood\u003C/strong\u003E - This is closer to the total oxygen content including haemoglobin-bound oxygen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E20 mL per 100 mL blood\u003C/strong\u003E - This exceeds the total oxygen carrying capacity of blood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E30 mL per 100 mL blood\u003C/strong\u003E - This is physiologically impossible under normal conditions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe amount of dissolved oxygen follows Henry\u0027s Law, meaning it increases linearly with the partial pressure of oxygen. This becomes clinically relevant in hyperbaric oxygen therapy where increased atmospheric pressure can significantly increase dissolved oxygen content.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dissolved oxygen accounts for only 3% of total oxygen content in blood, with the remaining 97% bound to haemoglobin.","At normal atmospheric pressure, the amount of dissolved oxygen in blood is approximately 0.3 mL per 100 mL.","The amount of dissolved oxygen follows Henry\u0027s Law, increasing linearly with partial pressure of oxygen."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64854"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18738"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64854"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T07:28:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T07:29:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11470"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79550"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"